{{Expand Luxembourgish|Jean-Pierre Nuel|date=October 2013}}
[[File:Jean-Pierre Nuel-101b.jpg|thumb|Jean-Pierre Nuel]]
'''Jean-Pierre Nuel''' (February 27, 1847 &ndash; August 21, 1920) was a [[Luxembourg]]ian-[[Belgium|Belgian]] [[ophthalmologist]] and [[physiologist]] who was a native of [[Tétange]].

In 1870 he earned his doctorate from the [[University of Ghent]], and became licensed to practice [[surgery]] and [[gynecology]] in Luxembourg. Subsequently, he opened a private practice in the town of [[Eich, Luxembourg|Eich]] (today part of [[Luxembourg City]]) and furthered his education in [[Vienna]], [[Bonn]] and [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]. During this time period, his interest shifted to [[ophthalmology]], and he was particularly inspired by the work of [[Franciscus Donders]] (1818–1889) at Utrecht.

In 1877 Nuel became a professor of ophthalmology in [[Catholic University of Leuven (1834–1968)|Louvain]], and later a professor of physiology in Ghent (1880). In 1885 he attained the chair of ophthalmology and physiology of sensory organs at [[University of Liège|Liège]]. In the field of [[otology]], he is credited with the discovery of the eponymous "space of Nuel", which is an interval between the outer [[organ of Corti|rods of Corti]] and the adjacent hair cells.<ref>[http://www.bartleby.com/107/pages/page1058.html] (Henry Gray (1825–1861). Anatomy of the Human Body.  1918)</ref>

== Selected writings ==
* ''Beitrag zur Kenntniss der Säugethierschnecke'', (1872).
* ''Recherches microscopiques sur l ’anatomie du limaçon des mammifères'', (1878).

