{{quality|reason=<out of date, obscure technical material without explanations, notability justification>|date=March 2014}}
'''Real-time outbreak and disease surveillance system (RODS)''' is a [[syndromic surveillance]] system developed by the [[University of Pittsburgh]], Department of Biomedical [[Informatics (academic field)|Informatics]].<ref name="RODS_LAB" group=""/>   It is "prototype developed at the University of Pittsburgh where real-time clinical data from emergency departments within a geographic region can be integrated to provide an instantaneous picture of symptom patterns and early detection of [[epidemic]] events."<ref name="Public health">''Public Health-Related Activities'' at the
[http://aspe.hhs.gov/sp/NHII/phrelated.html US HHS government website].  Accessed December 2, 2010.</ref>

RODS uses a combination of various monitoring tools.<ref name="Shmueli_2010" group=""/>
# The first tool is a [[moving average]] with a 120-day sliding phase-I-window.{{clarify|reason=wikilink for this?|date=December 2010}}
# The second tool is a nonstandard combination of [[CUSUM]] and [[EWMA]], where an EWMA is used to predict next-day counts, and a CuSum monitors the residuals from these predictions.
# The third monitoring tool in RODS is a [[recursive least squares]] (RLS) algorithm, which fits an [[autoregressive model]] to the counts and updates estimates continuously by minimizing [[prediction error]]. A Shewhart I-chart{{clarify|date=December 2010}} is then applied to the residuals, using a threshold of 4 [[standard deviations]].
# The fourth tool in RODS implements a [[wavelet]] approach, which decomposes the time series using [[Haar wavelet]]s, and uses the lowest resolution to remove long-term trends from the raw series. The residuals are then monitored using an ordinary Shewhart I-chart with a threshold of 4 standard deviations.

== References ==
